comments.text:
Education isn't determined in a whole in America, it's statewide decided. 
Each state has their own curriculum and own EOC exams. In Texas the grades 
go like this (highscool level) 
A+=95-100%
A-=90-94%
B+=85-89%
B-=80-84%
C+=75-79% (on some EOCs this would be just a 'C')
C-=70-74% (which is failing on most EOCs, but not tests such as STAAR)
D=65-69% (most schools consider this failing, but sometimes don't)
F=70,64-0% (the STAAR scores rank different- usually a 57% is the passing 
point on STAAR. 

Also, the remarks of how America has a low rank on education is purely 
wavered. In most countries you only let the best students attend school, or 
the best only take 'the' test. (Which I presume are the LSATs,SATs,ACTs.) 
While here in America we let EVERYBODY take 'the' test, off balancing are 
scores. ﻿

comments.text:
Where I live in Canada you get percentages on your report card and level 
grades on your tests. A is a 4, B is a 3, C is a 2, D is a 1, and F is an R 
(Remedial Standards). Just like with letter grades you can get a 4+ or a 4- 
with all the levels except an R.

4 - 100%-80%
3 - 79% - 70%
2 - 69% - 60%
1 - 59% - 50%
R - 49% - 0%﻿
